Now I have a complete picture of the codebase. Here's the full architecture analysis:

---

# Code & Architecture Sorcerer: Udderly Abduction Barrage

## Current State Analysis

**Codebase:** 5,706 lines across 2 files (game.js: 4,917, audio.js: 789). Single IIFE monolith. Vanilla JS + Canvas 2D at 480x270 upscaled 3x. Fixed 60fps timestep. Pre-allocated bullet pool (1,500), splice-based entity arrays for everything else, pixel-art font/sprite system, procedural + file-based audio.

**Critical pain points identified:**
- 850+ lines of static sprite/font data inline in game.js
- Entity arrays (cows, farmers, particles, etc.) still use push/splice (GC pressure)
- No spatial partitioning (bullet-UFO collision is O(n) over 1,500 every frame)
- All tunables are hardcoded constants scattered across 5,000 lines
- Zero modularity: adding a new enemy type means editing 4+ disconnected sections
- No profiling hooks; no way to know if you're hitting frame budget

---

## Step 1: Eight Architecture Approaches

### A1: Status Quo (Incremental Patching)
Keep the monolith. Fix problems as found. Add features by inserting code into existing sections.
- **Pros:** Zero refactor cost; ship features today
- **Cons:** Every addition makes the file harder to navigate; tunables stay scattered; no reuse; eventually hits a wall where changes break unrelated systems

### A2: File Split (ES Modules)
Split game.js into 8-12 ES modules: `entities.js`, `patterns.js`, `rendering.js`, `audio.js`, `input.js`, `hud.js`, `boss.js`, `balance.js`. Use `import/export`.
- **Pros:** Readable file sizes; team-friendly; IDE navigation
- **Cons:** Requires a local server (modules need CORS); introduces import dependency management; module load order matters; shared state needs an explicit state bus or global object

### A3: Entity-Component System (Data-Oriented)
Flat typed arrays for all entity data (positions, velocities, HP in Float32Arrays). Systems iterate contiguous memory. Components are just array indices.
- **Pros:** Cache-friendly; zero GC; trivially parallelizable; scales to 10,000+ entities
- **Cons:** Massive refactor; overkill for ~50 active entities + 1,500 bullets; debugging array indices is painful; pixel art rendering doesn't benefit from data locality the way 3D does

### A4: Component Composition (Lightweight)
Entities are plain objects but behaviors are composable "component" functions: `addFlee(entity)`, `addPatternShooter(entity)`, `addPhaseTransition(entity)`. Update loops call component update functions.
- **Pros:** New entity types = new component combos; no class hierarchies; components are testable in isolation
- **Cons:** Component interaction order matters (flee before move? after?); needs a component registry; adds indirection for a small team

### A5: State Machine + Data Tables
All entity behavior driven by explicit state machines (FSM per entity type). All numeric values in centralized data tables (JSON-like config objects). Game logic becomes: read state, look up data, transition state.
- **Pros:** Extremely tunable; designer-friendly; behavior is debuggable (print current state); new bosses = new state table entries
- **Cons:** Verbose for simple entities (cows don't need complex FSMs); state explosion for bosses with many phases

### A6: Event Bus + Systems
Decoupled systems communicate through a lightweight pub/sub event bus. `emit('cow-collected', {cow, position})` triggers scoring, particles, audio, bullet cancel, combo update independently.
- **Pros:** Systems don't know about each other; adding new reactions to events is trivial; perfect for juice (screen shake, particles, audio are just event listeners)
- **Cons:** Event ordering is implicit; debugging "what happened" requires tracing event chains; can become spaghetti if events trigger events

### A7: Object Pool Everything + Archetype Arrays
Pre-allocate pools for ALL entity types (not just bullets). Cows, farmers, particles, score popups, power-ups all use fixed-size pools with alive flags. Group by archetype for cache-friendly iteration.
- **Pros:** Zero GC during gameplay; predictable memory; splice elimination; pool exhaustion is a soft cap instead of unbounded growth
- **Cons:** Fixed pool sizes need tuning; entity initialization requires explicit reset of all fields; slightly harder to add new entity fields

### A8: Hybrid: Modules + Data Tables + Pools + Event Bus
Combine the best of A2, A5, A6, A7. ES modules for file organization. Data tables for all tunables. Object pools for hot-path entities. Event bus for juice/feedback decoupling.
- **Pros:** Each concern solved by the right tool; incrementally adoptable; scales from current scope to 10x content
- **Cons:** Most complex to set up; risk of over-engineering for a game that's already fun

---

## Step 2: Evaluation Matrix

| Approach | Performance (60fps) | Modularity | Scalability | Readability | Juice Integration | Testing | **AVG** |
|----------|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|
| A1: Status Quo | 6 | 2 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 2 | **3.2** |
| A2: ES Modules | 6 | 8 | 7 | 9 | 5 | 7 | **7.0** |
| A3: Full ECS | 10 | 9 | 10 | 4 | 5 | 6 | **7.3** |
| A4: Composition | 7 | 8 | 8 | 7 | 6 | 8 | **7.3** |
| A5: FSM + Tables | 7 | 7 | 8 | 8 | 5 | 8 | **7.2** |
| A6: Event Bus | 6 | 7 | 7 | 6 | 10 | 6 | **7.0** |
| A7: Pool Everything | 9 | 5 | 6 | 5 | 4 | 5 | **5.7** |
| **A8: Hybrid** | **9** | **9** | **9** | **8** | **9** | **8** | **8.7** |

---

## Step 3: The Winner — A8: Hybrid Architecture

**Why it wins ruthlessly:**

1. **Performance is non-negotiable.** 1,500 bullets iterated every frame at 60fps = 16.6ms budget. Pools eliminate GC stalls. The current `Array.splice` on cows/farmers/particles is a ticking time bomb when particle counts spike during boss fights + bullet cancel combos. Pools fix this.

2. **Juice IS the game.** Bullet-hell lives or dies on screen feel. The event bus means adding a new reaction to "cow collected" (screen flash, particles, bullet cancel, combo text, score pickup, audio, slowmo) is one line: `events.on('cow-collected', handler)`. Currently, cow collection touches 6 different code sections in a 200-line block. That's unmaintainable.

3. **Data tables unlock iteration speed.** Every balance tweak currently requires finding the right hardcoded number in a 5,000-line file. A `BALANCE` object means a designer (or a tuning agent) can adjust every value from one place. Boss definitions, pattern configs, difficulty curves, all become data, not code.

4. **ES modules make the 5,000-line monolith navigable.** Twelve 300-400 line files > one 5,000-line file. Period.

5. **It's incrementally adoptable.** You don't rewrite the game. You extract modules one at a time. Pool the particle array first. Add the event bus second. Extract data tables third. Each step is independently shippable.

---

## Step 4: Complete Implementation Guidance

### Project Structure

```
/src
  index.html
  main.js              # Entry point, game loop, RAF
  canvas.js            # Canvas setup, resize, offscreen buffer
  input.js             # Keyboard state, GAME_KEYS, justPressed
  events.js            # Lightweight pub/sub event bus
  balance.js           # ALL tunable values in one object
  state.js             # Game state machine (BOOT/MENU/PLAYING/etc)
  entities/
    pool.js            # Generic object pool factory
    ufo.js             # UFO create/update/render
    bullet.js          # Bullet pool + patterns + graze + cancel
    cow.js             # Cow create/update/render + flee AI + varieties
    farmer.js          # Farmer create/update/render + alerting + patterns
    boss.js            # Boss create/update/render + phases
    particle.js        # Particle pool + score pickups
    powerup.js         # Power-up create/update/render/apply
  rendering/
    sprites.js         # Sprite data + palette definitions (extracted from game.js)
    font.js            # Pixel font data + drawText/drawTextCentered
    hud.js             # HUD rendering (score, HP, energy, graze, bombs, combo)
    background.js      # Sky, hills, stars, clouds, ground
    effects.js         # Screen shake, flash, slowmo, transitions
    menu.js            # Menu/boot/game-over rendering
  audio.js             # AudioManager (already separate)
/assets
  *.wav, *.mp3, *.ogg  # Audio files
```

### Key Interfaces

#### Event Bus (`events.js`)
```javascript
// Zero-allocation event bus: pre-allocate listener arrays
const _listeners = {};

export function on(event, fn) {
  (_listeners[event] ||= []).push(fn);
}

export function off(event, fn) {
  const arr = _listeners[event];
  if (arr) {
    const idx = arr.indexOf(fn);
    if (idx >= 0) arr.splice(idx, 1);
  }
}

// Re-use a single detail object per event type to avoid allocation
const _details = {};
export function emit(event, detail) {
  const arr = _listeners[event];
  if (!arr) return;
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) arr[i](detail);
}

// Event catalog (string constants prevent typos)
export const EVT = {
  COW_COLLECTED:    'cow-collected',
  FARMER_KILLED:    'farmer-killed',
  UFO_HIT:          'ufo-hit',
  BOSS_HIT:         'boss-hit',
  BOSS_KILLED:      'boss-killed',
  BULLET_GRAZED:    'bullet-grazed',
  BULLET_CANCELLED: 'bullet-cancelled',
  BOMB_USED:        'bomb-used',
  POWERUP_COLLECTED:'powerup-collected',
  LEVEL_COMPLETE:   'level-complete',
  GAME_OVER:        'game-over',
  COMBO_MILESTONE:  'combo-milestone',
};
```

#### Generic Object Pool (`pool.js`)
```javascript
export function createPool(size, factory) {
  const items = new Array(size);
  for (let i = 0; i < size; i++) {
    items[i] = factory();
    items[i]._alive = false;
    items[i]._poolIndex = i;
  }

  // Free list for O(1) spawn (instead of linear scan)
  const free = [];
  for (let i = size - 1; i >= 0; i--) free.push(i);

  return {
    items,
    size,

    spawn(init) {
      if (free.length === 0) return null;
      const idx = free.pop();
      const item = items[idx];
      item._alive = true;
      init(item);
      return item;
    },

    kill(item) {
      if (!item._alive) return;
      item._alive = false;
      free.push(item._poolIndex);
    },

    forEach(fn) {
      for (let i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        if (items[i]._alive) fn(items[i]);
      }
    },

    killAll() {
      free.length = 0;
      for (let i = size - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        items[i]._alive = false;
        free.push(i);
      }
    },

    countAlive() {
      return size - free.length;
    }
  };
}
```

**Key improvement over current:** `spawnBullet` currently does O(n) linear scan to find a free slot. The free-list makes spawn O(1).

#### Balance Data Table (`balance.js`)
